docs.text: though made in canada , " overdrawn at the memory bank " traces its roots to the bbc school of film production .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: using , for the most part , cheap computer and video special effects , chyron text , wildlife documentary footage , and sets that are sometimes obviously faked up , it nonetheless manages to tell a good enough science fiction story that by the time you're twenty minutes into it , you should be hooked .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: raul julia plays aram fingal , a drone data processing worker for novicorp whose active imagination and predilection for hacking gets him into trouble with authority .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: caught watching " casablanca " on his desk monitor , fingal is sentenced to " doppling " rehabilitation--he is to spend forty-eight hours in the body of a baboon .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: ( how exactly this is supposed to rehabilitate him is anybody's guess . )
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as it happens , thanks to a visiting schoolboy's prank , his body is temporarily misplaced , and his mind has to be shunted into the central computer to keep him alive until they can find it .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as time ticks away before his memory cube self-destructs , the frantic search for his body is on . . . while
docs.label: positive

docs.text: fingal first creates a virtual reality fantasy world , then finds there's no better way to hack the system than from the inside .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: during the chaos , computer technician apollonia james ( linda griffiths ) maintains contact with fingal through a datalink , manifesting several different times to offer advice or warnings .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: over the course of their interactions , interest on both their parts grows into a budding romance .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: given that " casablanca " is fingal's favorite film , and the basis for his fantasy world , a great deal of the movie is homage to " casablanca " .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: in fact , the humphrey bogart and peter lorre characters make appearances ( played by julia in a dual role and louis negin , respectively ) in a bar called " the place " .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: julia's portrayal of bogart is passable , and avoids becoming the " schweethaat " -spouting parody seen in cartoons .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: negin's peter lorre is quite credible , and easily the best peter lorre i've ever seen who wasn't the real thing .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the two of them , as characters created by fingal's imagination , serve as aspects of his personality , driving him on in his quest to hack the computer system .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: those aren't the only casablanca characters to put in appearances .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the sydney greenstreet character also happens to be around . . . as " the fat man " , the alternate aspect of the film's main villain , the novicorp chairman ( donald c . moore ) .

docs.text: it's interesting to note the futuristic slang words that are thrown about left and right during the film , in the best golden-age science fiction tradition .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: words like " dopple " , " psychist " , " computech " , " cinema " , and " reconst " are apparently in common use .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: and while people of today may well laugh at fourteen years past's idea of futuristic data processing clerks , some aspects of this film are surprisingly perfectly in keeping with the way we think of " virtual reality " today .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: as cyberpunk films go , this may not be a staple of the genre , but it's definitely recommended viewing .

docs.text: the special effects are very primitive , placing this production in the realm of low-to-medium-budget television .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: the music is completely electronic-synthesized , which fits the low budget but isn't really out of keeping with the genre .
docs.label: positive

docs.text: however , the writing quite makes up for it .

docs.text: there are some very funny moments , and quite a few little in-jokes that one needs to have seen " casablanca " to appreciate properly .
